{<b>Bidding. </b>South uses a negative double to show that he would have responded
1\H. He should hold five hearts and at least 11 points to respond 2\H. South is
prepared to bid 2NT if North rebids 2\D.

North bids 2\H (13–16 support points), just as he would have done had South
responded 1\H.

South holds game-invitational strength, so bids once more. North holds a
maximum for the previous bidding and continues to game.

<b>Defense. </b>East holds unattractive holdings for leading spades, hearts, or clubs.
West cannot be expected to hold many values. The \DQ seems best. West can
encourage with the \D8 since she holds the \D10, an equivalent honor to East's
presumed \DJ.

<b>Declarer play. </b>Declarer counts six sure winners. Declarer hopes for a winning
spade finesse (very likely to work), a length trick from hearts, and two or
three additional tricks from clubs.

Declarer should duck one round of hearts to maintain control should they divide
4-1. She can then play \HK-A (unless East proves to hold four hearts) before
taking the club finesse.

Declarer should end up with at least 10 tricks for plus 420.

<b>Key point.</b> Bidding your own suit at the two-level or higher after an overcall
promises five cards. Double of a 1\S overcall shows four (or more) hearts and
eight or more points.  After making a negative double, responder may be
prepared to bid 2NT or 3NT if a major-suit fit isn't revealed.}
