{<b>Bidding. </b>North uses a negative double to show both minors. North isn't strong
enough to bid 2\C, though the good club suit is worth more than it looks.
Unless South shows some extra values then game is out of reach.

East should not raise spades. His spades are poor, he holds minimum values,
and he has no shortness to gain tricks by ruffing.

South does best to rebid 1NT with his decent spade holding. He should on no
account pass the double for penalties unless holding four spades (1\S goes set
only with perfect defense).

<b>Defense. </b>West should start with his fourth-best \S7. When leading your own
suit, lead an honor against a notrump contract only from a sequence. East
cannot contribute the \S9 or higher, so should give count with the \S2.

<b>Declarer play. </b>Declarer counts five sure winners. Clubs provide the best chance
for more.

Wanting to start clubs from her hand, declarer ducks the spade lead to his
jack. This is also the best play if East should hold a high honor in spades.
North then leads the \C9 (high card from the shorter side) for a double finesse,
playing low from dummy unless West plays the queen.

East will win the \CK and continue spades by playing the eight, highest of a
remaining doubleton. Declarer can hold up her ace, but West will persist with
spades.

Declarer now leads the \C5 for a second finesse of clubs. This wins, and the
\CA draws the queen. Declarer now has no fewer than nine tricks for plus 150.
Perhaps North should have bid more strongly!

<b>Key point.</b> Double of a 1\S overcall shows four (or more) hearts and eight or
more points. Opener rebids as if partner had responded 1\H.}
