{<b>Bidding. </b>South uses a negative double to show that he would have responded
1\H. South also holds the other unbid suit, clubs.

West should raise the spade overcall to 2\S or 3\S (weak). If West bids only
2\S, North holds 16 points in support of hearts, and stretches a point to rebid
3 \H. South holds enough to make game a good proposition.

If West bids 3\S, North should pass and South might double again to show extra
values.. North should then bid game in hearts. Note how West's preemptive
action can make it more difficult for South-North to reach game. 3\S goes set
one trick, so perhaps should be bid only if not vulnerable.

<b>Defense. </b>East should lead the \SK, highest of touching honors against a suit
contract, and should continue spades from the solid sequence.

<b>Declarer play. </b>Declarer counts five sure tricks. Declarer hopes for one more
from heart length, and can get three or four more from diamonds. If necessary,
the club finesse will have to be risked.

Declarer ruffs the second spade. Declarer wants to start diamonds from dummy,
so leads a low heart to the king. He then makes the key play of the \D 9,
playing low from his hand. When this draws the \D A, the rest should be easy.

Playing diamonds this way is indicated because East surely holds the \D A for
the overcall since she does not hold the \S A, and may well be short in
diamonds. Taking advantage of the \D 9 picks up the \D J x x x from West.

Declarer can finish with 11 tricks for plus 450.

<b>Key point.</b> In a competitive auction, jump raises of opening bids and overcalls
are weak based on a nine-card fit and less than constructive values (4-7
support points).}
