{<b>Bidding. </b>West's 1\H overcall does not keep North from responding 1\S. Most
would instead use a negative double to show exactly four spades, reserving a
1\S response to show five or more.

South raises spades,¹ just as she would have done had North responded 1\S. North
holds enough to bid game.

¹ Some would bid 2\S, as if responder bid 1\S, to show four spades and obstruct
overcaller's rebid.

<b>Defense. </b>West should lead the \HK, highest of touching honors against a suit
contract. East does not hold an equivalent honor (ace or jack) and so
discourages with the \H2.

West should note East's discouraging \H2 and switch to a passive club, the
\C8 (top of nothing) to deny strength in the suit.

<b>Declarer play. </b>Declarer counts seven sure winners and needs three more. One
additional trick might come from a successful spade finesse, and another from
spade length. A successful diamond finesse and a 3-3 division of clubs are two
additional chances, and perhaps a heart or club can be ruffed in dummy.

South should begin by ducking the opening lead of the \HK. Declarer has no
immediate discard for a heart loser, and the duck keeps West from continuing
hearts lest declarer score an undeserved trick with the \HJ.

Declarer can take the spade finesse either way. He would prefer to keep East
from leading a heart through his jack, so plays \SA and a low spade to the 10.
If West could win this trick, she still could not lead a second heart
productively.

When the spade finesse wins, declarer can play the \SK to draw the remaining
trump. Declarer now has ten tricks (with inevitable ruff in dummy), and can try
the diamond finesse for an overtrick. When the diamond finesse wins and the
clubs divide 3-3, declarer finishes with no fewer then 12 tricks for plus 680.
Some days everything works!

<b>Key point.</b> Double of a 1\H overcall shows exactly four spades. Bidding 1\S
shows five or more, which simplifies subsequent bidding decisions.}
