{<b>Bidding. </b>South uses a negative double to show that she would have responded
1\S. South also holds the other unbid suit, clubs.

North jumps in spades to show extra values (17–18 support points).

South reevaluates to 12 points, well enough to bid game.

<b>Defense. </b>East starts with the \DA, West encouraging with the seven since she
desires a ruff. East continues with high diamonds, and West should discard a
low heart on the third diamond. This preserves the club length to match that of
dummy, and at the same time prepares West to ruff hearts.

<b>Declarer play. </b>Declarer counts eight sure tricks. Declarer plans to develop
more by ruffing hearts and by heart length.

Declarer cannot draw trumps as they are required for ruffing hearts and for
entries to hand. Declarer starts with the \HA-K and a third heart to ruff in
dummy.

Somewhat disappointingly, West ruffs the third heart. Don't panic, you're not
set yet! West must return a club (or a trump). Declarer can now play a spade to
her hand and ruff another heart with the \SQ so that West cannot overruff. Now
the last spade from dummy allows declarer to pull trumps and enjoy her long
heart for plus 620.

<b>Key point.</b> Don't look down on shortness in opener's first suit when you're
dummy for opener's second suit. Ruffs are tricks, and can be used to establish
length winners.}
