{<b>Bidding. </b>North uses a negative double to show that she would have responded
1\H. She also holds the other unbid suit, diamonds.

South holds 20 points, too much to just jump to 3\C. 4\C is a possibility, but
that goes past 3NT. Best is to cue-bid 2\S, a general forcing bid, to leave
open the opportunity to play 3NT.

North has no spade guard for notrump, and can do no better than to show four
diamonds (in addition to the four hearts she already showed). South now shows
his hand by bidding 4\C. With nothing wasted for South-North in spades, North bids
game in clubs.

<b>Defense. </b>West should start with the \SA (highest of touching honors against a
suit contract), on which East should discourage with the two. Regardless,
West should continue with high spades. Knowing that East can have very little
given the bidding and her hand, West leaves it to declarer to find enough
tricks.

<b>Declarer play. </b>Declarer counts 10 sure tricks and needs one more. A successful
finesse of diamonds or hearts will land the contract, but a losing finesse will
sink the contract immediately.

Since declarer can try only one finesse, declarer first plays the A-K in one of
the suits to try to catch the queen.

<i>Chance 1. </i>Declarer should pull trump, then play \DA-K to see if the queen
drops. It does, declarer has eleven tricks for plus 600. South fulfills the
contract even though neither finesse is working!

<i>Chance 2. </i>Had the \DQ not fallen, only then would declarer have to risk the
heart finesse by playing \HK and a heart to the \HJ.

Why play off the high diamonds rather than the high hearts? A finesse is a
50-50 proposition, but not so catching a doubleton queen. Holding more combined
diamonds than hearts, it is more likely that a defender holds \DQ x than \HQ x.

<b>Key point.</b> Hands with a long minor suit and 19–21 points are awkward to bid.
After opening your suit, you may have to guess whether to jump to 3NT or make a
“prepared” reverse or jump-shift in a three-card suit.  •  As declarer, look
for ways to combine your various chances.}
